/* <orly/lang_tests/general/variants_recursive.orly>

   End-to-end test for issue #103: recursive sum types (self-referential
   variants), plus the alias-constructor form they require.

   A type def whose top level is a variant may refer to itself from an
   arm's payload -- directly (`W(tree)`) or as a field of the arm's
   payload record (`Branch(<{.l: tree, .r: tree}>)`). Construction goes
   through the TYPE DEF'S NAME, since a recursive type's literal cannot
   be written: `tree.Leaf(1)` takes a positional payload, `intlist.Nil()`
   constructs a tag-only arm. (The alias-ctor form works for any variant
   type def, recursive or not -- see t1/t2.)

   Everything from #95 composes: `is <Tag>` predicates, `.<Tag>` payload
   accessors (which yield the payload with self-references unrolled to
   the variant type itself), exhaustive `when` with payload binders, deep
   structural `==`, and membership in local sets. Folds over a recursive
   value are ordinary recursive functions (see factorial.orly).

   v1 limits, all reported as compile errors (verified by hand; lang_test
   has no "expect compile error" form):
     - mutual/transitive recursion (`a is <| X(b) |>; b is <| Y(a) |>;`)
       -> "has a cycle in its build dependencies"
     - a self-reference outside a variant arm (`t is <{.x: t}>;`)
       -> "a recursive type reference must appear inside a variant arm"
     - a self-reference under a container or nested variant
       (`t is <| X([t]) |>;`) -> "a self-reference may only appear as an
       arm's payload or as a field of an arm's payload record"
     - storing a recursive value (`<[1]> <- tree.Leaf(5);`)
       -> "a value containing a recursive variant cannot be stored"
   Returning a recursive value to a client throws at runtime (AsVar);
   recursive values are package-internal until the sabot type encoding
   can express recursion.

   Copyright 2010-2026 Atomic Kismet Company

   Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");
   you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.
   You may obtain a copy of the License at

     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0

   Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software
   distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,
   WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.
   See the License for the specific language governing permissions and
   limitations under the License. */

/* A flat variant, to pin the alias-ctor form on its own. */
op_t is <| Text(str) | Number(int) | Deleted |>;

/* The flagship: a binary tree. The self-references sit as fields of the
   `Branch` arm's payload record. */
tree is <| Leaf(int) | Branch(<{.l: tree, .r: tree}>) |>;

/* A linked list: tag-only base case (`Nil`), record cons cell. */
intlist is <| Nil | Cons(<{.head: int, .tail: intlist}>) |>;

classify = ((v) when {
  Text(t): t;
  Number: "num";
  Deleted: "gone";
}) where {
  v = given::(op_t);
};

/* Recursive folds: `when` selects the arm, the binder exposes the
   payload (unrolled, so `b.l` is a `tree` again), recursion descends. */
eval = ((t) when {
  Leaf(n): n;
  Branch(b): eval(.t: b.l) + eval(.t: b.r);
}) where {
  t = given::(tree);
};

leaves = ((t) when {
  Leaf: 1;
  Branch(b): leaves(.t: b.l) + leaves(.t: b.r);
}) where {
  t = given::(tree);
};

sum_list = ((xs) when {
  Nil: 0;
  Cons(c): c.head + sum_list(.xs: c.tail);
}) where {
  xs = given::(intlist);
};

/* Shared fixture values. */
t1v = (tree.Branch(<{.l: tree.Leaf(1), .r: tree.Leaf(2)}>)) where {};
t2v = (tree.Branch(<{.l: tree.Leaf(1), .r: tree.Leaf(2)}>)) where {};
t3v = (tree.Branch(<{.l: tree.Leaf(1), .r: tree.Leaf(3)}>)) where {};

l123 = (intlist.Cons(<{.head: 1, .tail:
        intlist.Cons(<{.head: 2, .tail:
        intlist.Cons(<{.head: 3, .tail: intlist.Nil()}>)}>)}>)) where {};

test {
  /* The alias-ctor form on a FLAT variant (works independently of
     recursion; closes the "aliases not usable as ctors" gap). */
  t1: classify(.v: op_t.Text("hello")) == "hello";
  t2: classify(.v: op_t.Deleted()) == "gone";

  /* Fold over a depth-3 tree built inline through the alias. */
  t3: eval(.t: tree.Branch(<{.l: tree.Leaf(3), .r:
              tree.Branch(<{.l: tree.Leaf(4), .r: tree.Leaf(5)}>)}>)) == 12;

  /* Structural equality all the way down. */
  t4: t1v == t2v;
  t5: t1v != t3v;

  /* is-destructuring and chained accessors on a recursive arm: the
     accessor's record fields are `tree` again (one unrolling). */
  t6: t1v is Branch;
  t7: not (t1v is Leaf);
  t8: (t1v.Branch).l is Leaf;
  t9: (t1v.Branch).l.Leaf == 1;

  /* Tag-only base case + fold over a 3-cell list. */
  t10: sum_list(.xs: l123) == 6;
  t11: sum_list(.xs: intlist.Nil()) == 0;

  /* Fold over an asymmetric tree. */
  t12: leaves(.t: tree.Branch(<{.l: t1v, .r: tree.Leaf(9)}>)) == 3;

  /* Recursive variants in a local set: hashing and ordering reach
     through the boxed payloads, so the duplicate collapses. */
  t13: length_of {t1v, t2v, t3v} == 2;
};
